<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-361-992  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 361 992.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  April 1990 v41 n4 p17(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How will the 1990s affect systems people? (Management informationroundtable) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reitzfeld, Milt.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Issues and events that will shape the systems managementprofession during the 1990s are examined.andP;  These include thecontinued improvement of information technology by the enhancementof the productive and storage capacity of chips, miniaturization,increased speed and reduced costs.andP;  Greater worldwide competitionfrom the European Community and the Pacific Rim will trigger anincreased focus in the US on management improvement.andP;  Statisticalinformation resulting from the 1990 US Census will be used toimprove domestic marketing, distribution and storage procedures.andO;Business publications will appear more often in electronic form,facilitating search, storage and retrieval more quickly and atreduced costs.andP;  Company-provided daycare, flextime schedules, andincreasing employment of mature personnel will all be institutedas ways of remaining competitive.andP;  Businesses will also be lookingat ways of improving the utilization and thereby reducing the costof office space.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Future of ComputingTrendsBusinessComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>